d care, and mental load, but also increased emotional labour. While some women were categorized as “essential,” others remained in the shadows – all faced unsustainable workloads, moral distress, and burnout, while continuing to demand better services for those in their care.An analysis of Canada’s COVID-19 response from the perspective of those who staffed it, Conscripted to Care presents crucial lessons for those interested in public health and how it relates to gender and economic equality, as well as public policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspectszCanada. 0aEqualityxHealth aspectszCanada. 0aEquality-Health aspects. 0aPublic healthzCanada. 0aPublic health-Canada. 0aWomen employeeszCanadaxEconomic conditionsy21st century. 0aWomen employeeszCanadaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aWomenzCanadaxEconomic conditionsy21st century. 0aWomenzCanadaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aPandemic.  acrisis.  adeterminants.  aeconomy.  aeducation.  aequality.  aessential workers.  afamily.  agender.  ahealth.  ahousehold.  ajustice.  alabour.  apathogen.  apolicy.  areproduction.  asocial.  avirus.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228019312?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228019312423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228019312/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles